tions of heritage in play for twenty-first-century Soqotra, Nathalie Peutz narrates how everyday Soqotrans came to assemble, defend, and mobilize their cultural and linguistic heritage. These efforts, which diverged from outsiders' focus on the island's natural heritage, ultimately added to Soqotrans' calls for political and cultural change during the Yemeni Revolution. Islands of Heritage shows that far from being merely a conservative endeavor, the protection of heritage can have profoundly transformative, even revolutionary effects. Grassroots claims to heritage can be a potent form of political engagement with the most imminent concerns of the present: human rights, globalization, democracy, and sustainability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCultural propertyxProtectionzYemen (Republic)zSocotra. 0aNature conservationzYemen (Republic)zSocotra. 4aArabian Peninsula. 4aSoqotra Archipelago. 4aYemen. 4aautochthony. 4adevelopment. 4aendemism. 4aenvironmental conservation. 4aheritage. 4alanguage endangerment. 4asovereignty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360715640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607156423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607156.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles